Why does it force me to use the ceil() function when I can just use the round() function to do the same thing?

The round and ceil functions aren’t interchangeable. The ceil function rounds fractions up, while the round function rounds a float to the closest integer.
Consider the example tipGenerously(66.18). If we add a 20% tip, the new total is 79.416.
If we round this i.e. round(79.416), we get 79 because 79.416 is more closer to the integer 79 than the integer 80. Contrast this with ceil(79.416) which results in 80. The motivation behind using ceil instead of round for calculating the total cost is that we are willing to pay a slight bit extra to ensure that the tip is 20%. If we round the total instead, then there is a chance that the tip may be a shade below 20%. So, we are willing to pay a few extra cents if necessary, but we don’t want to shortchange even by a few cents.

